Target Limited Outreach Resources for Home Repair Tax Credit Program.

The Department of Housing and Community Development (HCD) has been proactively reaching out to potential homeowners for a home repair tax credit program. However, the program has a low conversion rate and a high cost per successful applicant. It is evaluated that the houses that transacted after taking the credit can be sold with a $10,000 premium on average, and the homes surrounding the repaired home witness an aggregate premium of $56,000, on average. To maximize the benefit and minimize the cost of the program, a data-driven strategy is needed to prioritize the homeowners who are most likely to take the credit. By using the data from previous campaigns, we can predict the likelihood of a homeowner entering and taking the credit based on various indicators, including their characteristics and behavior, to inform a cost/benefit analysis that can optimize the allocation of outreach resources.

Feature Importance and Correlation

The first section aims to explore the relationship of each indicator with the result of entering the program or not. Both numeric and categorical variables are examined to understand their importance and correlation.

housing %>%
  dplyr::select(y, age, campaign, previous, unemploy_rate, cons.price.idx, 
                cons.conf.idx, spent_on_repairs) %>%
  gather(Variable, value, -y) %>%
    ggplot(aes(y, value, fill=y)) + 
      geom_bar(position = "dodge", stat = "summary", fun = "mean") + 
      facet_wrap(~Variable, scales = "free") +
      scale_fill_manual(values = palette2) +
      labs(x="Enter", y="Value", 
           title = "Feature associations with the likelihood of entering the program",
           subtitle = "(continous outcomes)",
           caption = "Figure 1") +
      theme(legend.position = "none")

There is a relatively higher concentration of entering the program in terms of age, number of contacts for this campaign and unemployment rate change at that time.

housing %>%
    dplyr::select(y, age, campaign, previous, unemploy_rate, cons.price.idx, 
                cons.conf.idx, spent_on_repairs, inflation_rate) %>%

    ggplot() +

    facet_wrap(~Variable, scales = "free") +

By exploring the numeric variables, it is found that there is a major difference in entering the program based on the age, consumer confidence, consumer price, inflation, previous contacts, money spent on repairs and the unemployment rate.

Because of the inadequate sensitivity of the existing variables, we engineered new variables that aim to enhance the predictability of the homeowners’ possibility to enter the program or not. They are: - edu (below and with high school degree, above high school degree, unknown), - season (Winter, Spring, Summer, Fall), - job.y.share (the share of people entering the program based on each type of job), - pdays_cat (whether the homeowner was contacted or not), - repair_cat (whether the house repair cost is less than $5175 or above).

housing <- housing %>%
  mutate(edu = ifelse((education =="university.degree" | education =="professional.course"), "aboveHS", ifelse(education == "unknown" | is.na(education), "unknown", "belowHS")))

housing <- housing %>%
  mutate(season = case_when(
    month == "dec" | month == "jan" | month == "feb" ~ "Winter",
    month == "mar" | month == "apr" | month == "may" ~ "Spring", 
    month == "jun" | month == "jul" | month == "aug" ~ "Summer",
    month == "sep" | month == "oct" | month == "nov" ~ "Fall"))

housing <- housing %>%  
  group_by(job) %>% 
  summarize(tot.y = sum(y_numeric), 
            n = n(), 
            job.y.share = 100*(tot.y/n)) %>% 
  dplyr::select(-n, -tot.y) %>% 
  right_join(housing, .) 

housing <- housing %>%
  mutate(pdays_cat = ifelse(pdays == 999, "no", "yes"))

housing <- housing %>%
  mutate(repair_cat = ifelse(spent_on_repairs >= 5175, ">= 5175", "< 5175"))
housing %>%
    dplyr::select(y, marital, edu, mortgage, contact, poutcome, taxLien, taxbill_in_phl, season,
                  pdays_cat, repair_cat) %>%
    gather(Variable, value, -y) %>%
    count(Variable, value, y) %>%
      ggplot(., aes(value, n, fill = y)) +   
        geom_bar(position = "dodge", stat="identity") +
        facet_wrap(~Variable, scales="free") +
        scale_fill_manual(values = palette2, name = "Entered the program?") +
        labs(x="Variable", y="Value",
             title = "Feature associations with the likelihood of entering the program",
             subtitle = "Categorical features",
             caption = "Figure 3") +
        theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

This figure shows that the homeowners who are contacted by cellular, have been previously contacted, have less money spent on house repair are more likely to enter the program.

Model Evaluation

We ran both kitchen sink model and our feature engineered model. Based on the pseudo-R2 measures, it shows that the kitchen sink model is better than the feature engineered model in terms of explaining the variability in the outcome variable because the McFadden score of kitchen sink model is higher, which indicates a better fit to the data. Despite the effort to engineer new features, the kitchen sink model still has better fit. Nevertheless, new features can be used for more comprehensive examination of the real world issue as the McFadden score of feature engineered model is close to the kitchen sink model’s.

                  family="binomial" (link="logit"))

We performed cross validation for both kitchen sink model and the feature engineered model. Both models are better at predicting negatives than positives. We used ROC curve as it visualizes trade-offs for two important confusion metrics, while also providing a single goodness of fit indicator. Both models show good fit as the curves are above the diagonal line with close values of ROC. Meanwhile, for the kitchen sink and featured engineered models, the sensitivity is 0.980 and 0.983 respectively, and the specificity is 0.219 and 0.212. The results indicate that both models have good sensibility that predict the result correctly.

Cost-Benefit Analysis

  • True Negative: no marketing resources were allocated, and no credit was allocated. True_Negative = Count * 0

  • True Positive: allocated the marketing resources ($2,850), and 25% ultimately achieved the credit ($5,000), with $10,000 premium on average per household and an aggregate premium of $56,000 on average. True_Positive = (-2850) * Count - (5000 * .25) * Count + (10000 + 56000) * Count * .25

  • False Negative: no marketing resources were allocated, and no credit was allocated. False_Negative = Count * 0

  • False Positive: allocated the marketing resources ($2,850). False_Positive = (-2850) * Count

cost_benefit_table <-
   testProbs %>%
      count(predOutcome, Outcome) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==0]),
                True_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==0])) %>%
       gather(Variable, Count) %>%
       mutate(Revenue =
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Negative", Count * 0,
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Positive",((-2850) * Count - (1250) * Count + 16500 * Count),
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Negative", Count * 0,
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Positive", (-2850) * Count, 0))))) %>%
    bind_cols(data.frame(Description = c(
              "We correctly predicted not entering credit program",
              "We correctly predicted entering credit program",
              "We predicted not entering credit program and customer entered",
              "We predicted entering credit program and customer did not")))

kable(cost_benefit_table,
       caption = "Cost/Benefit Table") %>% kable_styling()

iterateThresholds <- function(data) {
  x = .01
  all_prediction <- data.frame()
  while (x <= 1) {
  
  this_prediction <-
      testProbs %>%
      mutate(predOutcome = ifelse(Probs > x, 1, 0)) %>%
      count(predOutcome, Outcome) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==0]),
                True_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==0])) %>%
     gather(Variable, Count) %>%
     mutate(Revenue =
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Negative", Count * 0,
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Positive",((-2850) * Count - (1250) * Count + 16500 * Count),
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Negative", Count * 0,
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Positive", (-2850) * Count, 0)))),
            Threshold = x)
  
  all_prediction <- rbind(all_prediction, this_prediction)
  x <- x + .01
  }
return(all_prediction)
}
whichThreshold <- iterateThresholds(testProbs)

Conclusion

In general, this featured engineered model is recommended to the city because of its ability to predict true positives, which are those who will enter the program and take the credit. It benefits the improvement of the housing quality in the local community and contributes to housing equity in the long term for the entire city. However, this model also shows high cost of false positives which could result in additional cost. The model can be enhanced by introducing more features of income level, public facilities and spatial context.

To ensure that the marketing materials resulted in a better response rate, HCD should reach out to people when the unemployment rate is high, reach out to people with cellular more often and to those who spend less than $5175 on house repair.
